Part A

You must create a table that shows the courses you are currently enrolled in, using the following for the headers of the table:

  • Prefix: in bold letters (such as COP)
  • Number: in bold letters (such as 2073)
  • Name: in italics (such as Introduction to Data Science)
  • Credits (such as 3)
tab <- matrix(c("COP", "2073", "Intro to Data Science", "3","FIN" , "2001", "Intro to Business Finance", "3", "Eco", "2013", "Principles of Macroeconomics", "3"), ncol=4, byrow=TRUE)
colnames(tab) <- c('Prefix:','Number:','Name:','Credits')
rownames(tab) <- c('Class 1','Class 2','Class 3')
tab <- as.table(tab)
print(tab)

Intro to Business Finance

  • The Federal Reserve acts with monetary policy
  • The US Government acts with fiscal policy Source

Principles of Macroeconomics

  • GDP is private consumption + gross private investment + government investment + government spending + (exports – imports)
  • GDP per capita is a country’s GDP divided by its total population

Problem 4 (25 points)

  1. (10 points) Define a function imperial_to_metric that takes in two arguments: a number of feet and a number of inches. The function should return the equivalent length in meters
imperical_to_metric <- function(feet, inches) {
  meters <- ((feet * 12) + inches) * 0.0254
  return(meters)
}

To convert a length L from feet (ft) and inches (inches) to meters (m), one can use the relation: L(m) = L(ft) × 0.3048 + L(inches) × 0.0254

  1. (5 points) Create a variable height_in_meters by passing your height in imperial to the imperial_to_metric function.
height_in_meters <- imperical_to_metric(5,10)
height_in_meters
[1] 1.778
